// ENIAC specifications
// Tubes: 17,468
// Weight: 30 tons
// Power: 150 kW
// Floor space: 1,800 sq ft
// Speed: 5,000 ops/second
// 
// Comparison:
// Human computer: 40 hours per trajectory
// ENIAC: 30 seconds per trajectory
// Speedup: ~5,000√ó

// ENIAC programming model
// No stored program!
// 
// To compute a trajectory:
// 1. Plug cables to connect accumulators
// 2. Set switches for constant values
// 3. Configure function tables for ballistic data
// 4. Test the configuration
// 5. Run the computation
// 
// Setup time: Days
// Run time: Seconds

// ENIAC digit storage
// Ring counter: 10 flip-flops per digit
// Only one flip-flop 'on' at a time
// Value 0: First flip-flop on
// Value 9: Tenth flip-flop on
// 
// Binary alternative:
// 4 flip-flops store 0-15
// More efficient, less intuitive
// 
// ENIAC used decimal because
// humans think in decimal

